Web Scraping using Premier League Data 21/22¶

Using the library BeautifulSoup, I will be scraping and parsing through HTML data to create several dataframes and graphs to analyze Premier League data from the 2021/2022 season. Below I have imported all the libraries I will be utilizing to help with my analysis.

Webscraping using FBref¶

FBref.com is a free website that provides full coverage data and stats of football leagues all around the world. I will specifically be using the Premier League stats of the 21/22 season in order to retrieve relevant data such as the number of wins, losses, goals scored, goals expected, etc to summarize and explain what happened during that season.

Using BeautifulSoup, we will extract our data table using the HTML parser.

In [2]:
#Take site and structure html
URL = 'https://fbref.com/en/comps/9/2021-2022/2021-2022-Premier-League-Stats'
page = requests.get(URL)

soup = BeautifulSoup(page.content, "html.parser")
results = soup.find('table', id="results2021-202291_overall")

#Find all column names in table of website
headers = []

for i in results.find_all('th'):
 title = i.text
 headers.append(title)

Goal Difference¶

Goal difference is calculated as the following: GD = GF - GA, which means we subtract the goals conceded from the goals scored. From the plot below, we can see Norwich had the worst goal difference while Man City had the best.

A negative value indicates that the team had more goals against them. A positive value indicates that a team scored more goals than recieved. We can see that teams like Manchester United had a goal difference of 0 which indicates they scored the same number of goal that they recieved.

Expected Goals in the Season vs Actual Goals¶

Source: https://footballxg.com/

Expected goals (xG) calculates how many goals a team should have scored based on the quality of the chances created. It is a more accurate and fairer assessment than shots on targets. By comparing xG scores vs the actual goals scored, we can determine the teams scoring performance. For example, if the xG vs Actual value is negative, then the team scored less then they were expected to. If the value was positive, then the team overacheived by scoring more than what was expected.

Q: How does expected goals (xG) compare to the actual goals scored during the season?

Below in the dataframe, the xG was subtracted from the actual scored goals to give us the difference between actual vs expected.

  • In the 21/22 season, Leicester City scored about 14 more goals than was expected. On the other hand, Norwich scored around 9 less goals than they were expected to. In simple terms, it can be stated that Leicester overachieved in goal scoring since they scored around 14 (~14.2) goals than was predicted during the season.

Attendance at Home Matches vs Total Wins in Season¶

Q: Did the attendance at home matches during the 21/22 season affect the number of wins?

Although there needs to be more data to determine if there is an advantage when playing a home match or if the attendance numbers have any influence on the number of matches won, I attempted to do a correlation test using the average attendance per home match and the number of wins in the 21/22 season.

Below I used a scatter plot to display attendance vs game wins.

In [27]:
#Scatter plot for attendance vs wins

plt = px.scatter(mydata, x = "Attendance", y = "W", color = 'Squad', 
                trendline="ols", trendline_color_override = 'black', trendline_scope="overall")

plt.update_layout(
            title={
            'text' : "<b>Attendance per Game vs Wins in Season",
            'x':0.5,
            'xanchor': 'center'
        })

plt.show()

Using the pearsonr function from the scipy library, I was able to find the correlation coefficent as well as the two tailed p-value to determine if there was any relationship or significance regarding both variables (attendance/wins).

  • The correlation coefficent r = 0.6496

  • The 2-tailed p-value = 0.0019

The correlation coefficient tells us that there is a good/moderate positive correlation between attendance and wins. The closer to 1, the strong the positive correlation is. This positive correlation can be interpreted as the following: the more people attend a home match, then the higher number of wins during the season.

The p-value also suggests that there is a statistically significant association between both variables.

We can state that during the 21/22 season, there was a slight correlation between attendance and winning.

In [13]:
mydata['Attendance'].corr(mydata['W'])


r_coef = pearsonr(mydata['Attendance'], mydata['W'])[0]
p_val = pearsonr(mydata['Attendance'], mydata['W'])[1]

print("Correlation coefficent:",r_coef)
print("p-value:",p_val)

Creating a Dataframe for 90 Minute Stats¶

I also wanted to analyze the season by looking at the per-90-minute statistics. These per 90 stats measure certain values over the 90 minute period of a match. Using the 2nd table called Squad Standard Stats from the FBref website, I created 2 distinct dataframes with the information I wanted and concatenated them.

Concatenating 2 Dataframes¶

The first three columns of this data frame will contain the average number of players used throughout the season, the average age of each team (age weighted by minutes played) and the average possession of the ball.

The remaining columns will be the per 90 minute stats such as goals/90, assists/90, etc.

Below is the code used to scape data from another table on the FBref website and looping through the parsed data to store into a new dataframe.

Table Definitions:

  • G+A: Goals and Assists

  • G-PK: Goals - Penalty kicks made (essentially non-penalty goals)

  • XG : Expected goals, including penalties

  • npxG: Expected non-penalty goals

Yellow Cards vs Possession¶

Q: Is there a correlation between ball possession and accumalated yellow cards during a match?

Below I simply graphed ball possession vs yellow cards recieved per team. I also graphed the trendline, which shows a slight negative slope.

In [28]:
plt = px.scatter(per90stats, x="Poss", y="CrdY", color = 'Team', 
                trendline="ols", trendline_color_override = 'black', trendline_scope="overall")

plt.update_layout(
            title={
            'text' : "<b>% Ball Possesion vs Yellow Cards",
            'x':0.5,
            'xanchor': 'center'
        })

plt.update_traces(marker_size=10)

plt.show()

Once again, using the pearsonr function from the scipy library, I was able to find the correlation coefficent as well as the two tailed p-value to determine if there was any relationship or significance regarding both variables (ball possession/yellow cards).

  • The correlation coefficent r = -0.4021

  • The 2-tailed p-value = 0.0788

The correlation coefficient tells us that there is a moderate negative correlation between ball possession and yellow cards. The closer to -1, the strong the negative correlation is. This negative correlation would be interpreted as the following: the higher a team maintained possession of the ball during a match, then the team would recieve less yellow cards during the match.

The p-value from this data though, suggests that there is a somewhat of a statistically insignificant association between both variables since the value is closer to 1 and indicates the possibility that the results occured by random chance.

Non-penalty Goals¶

For the scatter plot below, I wanted to use the non-penalty statistics since comparing the goals and expected goals of each team with no penalties gives us a more accuate performance. Penalties have a higher probability (xG) to be scored, therefore the xG/90 can be affected if penalties are utilized in the calculation.

Below, I graphed the non-penalty goals vs expected non-penalty goals of each team per 90 min match. I also graphed a linear line (y = x), which helps indicate whether the teams are over/under performing (xG probability ranges from 0-1). The teams below the linear line, have scored less actual goals per 90 mins than was expected. On the other hand, those above the red line performed better than was expected.

There were a total of 6 teams during the 21/22 season that scored less actual goals than expected per 90 minutes of a match. These teams were Brentford, Brighton, Burnley, Leeds United, Norwich City, Southampton, Watford, and Wolves.
